My dear Mr Hodges! I think the Revd. Mr Buhlers sickness was occasioned by
the fatigue incurred in walking to Koterg to attend to business regarding
the Mission house there. If he had had a pony he might now, humanly speak-
ing, be alive. - From what I have seen, the Basle Committee treat their
Missionaries in a niggardly manner. This is very bad economy. It defeats
itself. It may be said that their unwillingness to allow more than one pony
at Kaity has sacrificed a valuable and devoted man. - I have never heard
any complaint from their Missionaries. I have only had occasion to admire
their earnest zeal and meek endurance of hardship and poverty. I ground my
opinion upon my own observations and upon what I have been able to learn on
inquiry. I know no Miss[ionar]y Soc. which treats its Missionaries as the
Basle Com. does and I pray that God may soon grant them a more sympathizing
heart and a more liberal hand.

I should be happy to have this expression of my sentiments and feelings
transmitted to the gentlemen of the Basle Com.

